english:
  title: Journey in Late Winter
  author: Seol Son
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Late winter snow drifts down upon the Konlung road,
    A single sail cuts swift as any bird.
    We venture deep into the mountain stream, pointing toward Hyesan,
    When suddenly the lonely city fades—waters and clouds grow distant.

    The yellow marsh grass on the sandy shore bends high and low,
    While green pines and jade bamboo rise above the clouds.
    House after house nestle in the woods—pottery kilns and forges,
    Each humble thatched roof flying banners of fermented wine.

    Gazing south, I spy the hermitage of the Huh clan,
    Where my old friend dwells deep among the plum blossoms.
    We made a pact to visit Tiger Hill again someday,
    But tonight my small boat must rest here in the twilight.
  footnotes:
    - 'Konlung road: a reference to travel through mountainous terrain'
    - 'Tiger Hill (호구산): likely a famous scenic location known to the poet and his friend'
    - The wine banners (주기) hung from taverns signal the presence of settlements amid nature
    - The poem captures the melancholy of winter travel interwoven with memories of friendship and unfulfilled promises
